5
00:01:14,520 --> 00:01:20,240
You can read a great novel, listen to a great symphony, or go to see a painting by a great

6
00:01:20,240 --> 00:01:26,800
artist, and you'll want to experience it again and again. And every time you do, you'll

7
00:01:26,800 --> 00:01:34,520
learn something new from it. Very few films achieve this. Most of them are mere entertainment

8
00:01:34,520 --> 00:01:40,400
and very few of them could be said to be works of art. They simply don't have the depth

9
00:01:40,400 --> 00:01:45,320
that a work of art has, and this means that you may see them once, but you won't want

10
00:01:45,320 --> 00:01:48,080
to watch them again.

11
00:01:48,080 --> 00:01:55,000
Why is it that so many commercial films today have such a limited shelf life? One problem

12
00:01:55,000 --> 00:01:59,920
is that for many films, once you've seen them once and you know what happens, that's

13
00:01:59,920 --> 00:02:06,160
it. They rely on the element of surprise to keep you interested, and once that's lost,

14
00:02:06,160 --> 00:02:10,960
that feeling of what's going to happen next, there's nothing left.

15
00:02:10,960 --> 00:02:16,520
In addition, the commercial nature of filmmaking means that rather than focusing on the development

16
00:02:16,520 --> 00:02:22,920
of characters in the film, many films are just becoming vehicles for actors, box office

17
00:02:22,920 --> 00:02:29,400
successes, who essentially play the same part each time. Then, as well as this, many critics

18
00:02:29,400 --> 00:02:34,800
would argue that the greatest black and white films had their own special world with

19
