its own special atmosphere, and that nowadays it's harder to create this because the director

20
00:02:40,960 --> 00:02:44,760
is unable to play with light in the same way.

21
00:02:44,760 --> 00:02:50,040
Another problem is that many directors lack the ability to focus the camera on the important

22
00:02:50,040 --> 00:02:56,240
points. There may be impressive visual images, but they don't contribute to the meaning

23
00:02:56,240 --> 00:03:02,320
of the film.

24
00:03:02,320 --> 00:03:10,120
Which brings me on to Ingmar Bergman, the great Swedish film director who died in 2007.

25
00:03:10,120 --> 00:03:16,760
No other director has equaled Bergman in his ability to convey emotion. His films have

26
00:03:16,760 --> 00:03:23,720
the dramatic force of a work by the world's greatest playwrights such as Ibsen or Shakespeare.

27
00:03:23,720 --> 00:03:31,080
Watching Bergman's films is an enriching experience. Nothing is immediately obvious or predictable,

28
00:03:31,080 --> 00:03:35,480
but gradually it becomes clear where he is taking you.

29
00:03:35,480 --> 00:03:42,560
If you study a film such as Wild Strawberries, you'll see that every little detail is significant.

30
00:03:42,560 --> 00:03:48,680
Each image on the screen is there for a purpose, and gradually builds up an understanding

31
00:03:48,680 --> 00:03:55,400
of the central meaning. With Bergman too, you know that a small gesture made by a character

32
00:03:55,400 --> 00:04:02,400
or the expression on a character's face can tell you just as much as the words uttered.

33
00:04:02,400 --> 00:04:07,800
In his film Persona, the central character says nothing, but meaning is conveyed by

34
00:04:07,800 --> 00:04:10,840
what we see on the screen.

35
00:04:10,840 --> 00:04:16,840
But Bergman wasn't just a great cinematographer. He was also a great storyteller.

36
00:04:16,840 --> 00:04:23,280
Each of his films follows a similar pattern in that the story is organized on two levels.

37
00:04:23,280 --> 00:04:29,520
Firstly, on the level of a straightforward, dramatic narrative. But secondly, on the level

38
00:04:29,520 --> 00:04:35,640
of myth, and the story works throughout the film on both these levels.

39
00:04:35,640 --> 00:04:41,080
In Bergman's film Wild Strawberries, an old man travels back to the places he knew as

40
00:04:41,080 --> 00:04:48,240
a child and a young man. In the film, we can identify themes that occur again and again

41
00:04:48,240 --> 00:04:54,960
in Bergman's work. First of all, we have the idea of the journey. Part of the journey

42
00:04:54,960 --> 00:05:01,720
is a real one, but linked with that is the theme of dreams, where they can take us and

43
00:05:01,720 --> 00:05:06,360
what we can learn from them. Another theme, which was to be central

44
00:05:06,360 --> 00:05:12,120
to Bergman's work throughout his life, is that of relationships, and in particular,

45
00:05:12,120 --> 00:05:19,000
the ties that join the members of a family together. And finally, as the old man in Wild

46
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:24,680
Strawberries struggles to make sense of his life, we have another theme which underlies all

47
00:05:24,680 --> 00:05:31,560
his work. No matter how anxious or unhappy his characters may appear to be, and that

48
00:05:31,560 --> 00:05:39,000
is, that we have to accept everything that life can give. It's not a fashionable philosophy,

49
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:47,360
and it may be why Bergman's films have fallen out of fashion.

